tegory><gtr:grantReference>G84/6588</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Continuity of care is said to be a defining feature of primary care. Traditionally, this meant a patient always seeing the same GP. However, changes in the way practices are organised mean that people are more likely to be looked after by a team of doctors and nurses. Research has shown that having a personal doctor-patient relationship is still thought to be important, but we do not know how important it is to see the same doctor in order to develop this relationship.

Depression and anxiety are very common and may go undetected by their GP. Whether continuity plays a part has not been examined. Symptoms of mental illness can be difficult for patients to disclose, and our theory is that patients are more likely to talk about them with a known and trusted doctor.
 
By developing a new questionnaire to measure the doctor-patient relationship, researchers at Bristol University plan to investigate the relationship between the length and the depth of the doctor-patient relationship. This new measure will then be used to see if higher continuity of doctor, a deeper doctor-patient relationship, or both, means GPs are more likely to detect patients who are suffering from depression or anxiety. This may lead to effective treatment and benefit patients.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Research into continuity of patient care has mainly examined associations between measures of longitudinal care (care provided over time) and outcomes in medical conditions. Work is needed to examine how longitudinal care contributes to the depth of the doctor-patient relationship, which may be a more significant determinant of benefits to patients. The depth of the doctor-patient relationship may determine a patient?s willingness to disclose symptoms of depression and anxiety, conditions which appear to be under-detected by general practitioners (GPs).
This is a two-phase study designed to examine the relationship between longitudinal care, depth of doctor-patient relationship, and the association of these factors with the detection of depression and anxiety. In the first phase, a new questionnaire to assess the depth of the doctor-patient relationship will be designed and psychometrically tested. The second phase will comprise a cross-sectional study of 300 adults attending 30 GPs. Data will be collected on consecutive attendees? mental state, their record of longitudinal care with the GP seen on the day, and the depth of doctor-patient relationship. These measures will be collected using the 12-item General Health Questionnaire, fraction of care continuity score, and the newly designed questionnaire respectively. For each patient, the GP will record the presence or absence of depression or anxiety, and provide an overall assessment of the depth of doctor-patient relationship using a Likert-type scale. Adjusting for confounding factors, multivariable regression analysis will be used to examine the data for relationships between longitudinal care and depth of doctor-patient relationship (separately considering the patient questionnaire and the doctor Likert scale scores), and between longitudinal care, depth of doctor-patient relationship and the detection of depression and anxiety. Consideration will be given to clustering by GP using random effects models.
 study will build on the body of research on the doctor-patient relationship, and the applicant?s own qualitative work with GPs. The department includes researchers who have published in the field of detection of common mental disorders in primary care. Professors Sharp, Peters, Goldberg and Freeman have agreed to collaborate on this project. Professors Sharp and Peters are divisional members with experience and expertise in primary care mental health and health services research respectively. Professor Goldberg (King?s College) and Professor Freeman (Imperial College) are international authorities in the areas of mental illness detection and continuity of patient care respectively.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>201521</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Letter</gtr:description><gtr:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>24AE8013-3749-450D-8ED2-3CB646D4A6D0</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Letters to patient participants who took part in questionnaire development, informing them of outcome.

